10":"1362–1410","1363–1410":"1363–1410","1363":"1363","1462":"1462","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1362":"1362","1470":"1470","1390":"1390","1435":"1435","1534":"1534","1456":"1456","Abt 1410":"about 1410","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1398":"1398","1397":"1397","Downton, Herefordshire, England":"Downton, Herefordshire, England","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Bramford, Suffolk, England":"Bramford, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Collins","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: variant of   Colin  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Irish and Manx: shortened Anglicized from <b>Ó Coileáin</b>, compare   Cullen  , or in Man or west Ulster shortened from <b>Mac Coileáin</b>, compare   McQuillan   and   McCallion  . The genitival <i>-s</i> is a local addition to   Collin   and variants after the surname was Anglicized.","Americanized form of French   Colin   or   Collin   and also   Collette  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Colin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Alfredo, Francisco, Jesus, Ricardo, Alberto, Angel, Arturo, Eduardo, Esteban, Faustino.  French Alexandre, Andre, Armand, Georges, Henri, Jean Claude, Jean-Michel, Laurette, Lucien, Marcel, Patrice, Pierre.","French, Walloon, and Breton: from a French shortened pet form of the personal name   Nicolas   (see   Nicholas  ). This surname is also found in the Flemish part of Belgium.","English: from the personal name <i>Colin</i>, a diminutive of <i>Col</i>, itself a pet form of   Nicholas  ."]},{"name":"Kolenc","meanings":["Slovenian:","topographic name derived from <i>koleno</i> ‘knee’.","nickname from the dialect plant name <i>kolenc</i> ‘yellow bedstraw (Galium verum)’ or ‘common nipplewort (Lapsana communis)’. Compare   Collins   3."]},{"name":"Callins","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Collins  ."]},{"name":"Collings","meanings":["English: variant of   Collins   or   Colling  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":45,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Collins was born in 1410, in Downton, Herefordshire, England, his father, David Collins, was 48 and his mother, Sarah Finley, was 47. He had at least 1 son with Manerva Amos. He died in 1456, in Bramford, Suffolk, England, at the age of 46."},"et":{"1410–1456":"1410–1456","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1396–Female":"1396–Surnud","1397–Male":"1397–Surnud","1398–1462":"1398–1462","1420–1470":"1420–1470","1435–1534":"1435–1534","1362–1410":"1362–1410","1363–1410":"1363–1410","1363":"1363","1462":"1462","1396":"1396","1395":"1395","1362":"1362","1470":"1470","1390":"1390","1435":"1435","1534":"1534","1456":"1456","Abt 1410":"umbes 1410","1455":"1455","1410":"1410","1420":"1420","1398":"1398","1397":"1397","Downton, Herefordshire, England":"Downton, Herefordshire, England","London, Middlesex, England":"Lon